New Rules for the Global Economy
CAMBRIDGE, MASS.: Let's assume that the world's top politicians would meet again in Bretton Woods, New Hampshire, to design a new global economic order.
They would naturally focus primarily on today's problems: the eurozone crisis, global recovery, financial regulation, international macroeconomic imbalances, etc. However, dealing with these issues would force the gathered leaders to go beyond and reconsider the overall solidity of the global economic arrangements.
Here are seven principles based on common sense for global economic governance, which they might agree on.
(I discuss these in more detail in my new book, The Globalization Paradox.)
1. Markets must be deeply embedded in existing regulatory systems.
The notion that markets can self-regulate has suffered a fatal blow in the recent financial crisis and should be buried once and for all.
Markets need other social institutions to support them.
They rely on courts, legal systems, and regulatory bodies to establish and enforce rules.
They depend on the stabilization functions provided by central banks and countercyclical fiscal policy.
They need the political acceptance that is brought forth by redistributive taxation, safety nets, and social security.
And all of this is equally valid for global markets.
2. In the foreseeable future, democratic state leadership will largely be organized within national political communities.
The nation-state lives, even if it may be a bit weak, and remains the main player in the game.
The pursuit of a world government is a futile endeavor.
Dass die nationalen Regierungen erhebliche Kontrollgewalt an die transnationalen Institutionen abgeben, ist kaum zu erwarten; zudem würde eine Regelharmonisierung Gesellschaften mit unterschiedlichen Bedürfnissen und Präferenzen nichts nutzen.
The European Union could be the only exception to this axiom, although its current crisis seems to be more of a proof against it.
International cooperation too often squanders effort on overambitious goals. Ultimately, it produces weak results that represent the lowest common denominator between the major countries.
If international cooperation is „successful“, it produces rules that are either toothless or reflect the preferences of the more powerful nations.
The Basel rules on capital requirements and the World Trade Organization rules on subsidies, intellectual property, and investment measures typify this type of overambitious effort.
We can strengthen the efficiency and legitimacy of globalization by supporting democratic procedures in our own country, rather than tearing them apart.

3. Pluralistischer Wohlstand: The admission that the central institutional infrastructure of the global economy has to be built on the national level gives individual countries the freedom to develop institutions that best suit their needs.
The US, Europe, and Japan have long-term comparable well-being in the long run.
However, their labor markets, corporate governance, cartel regulations, social security, and financial systems differ significantly, and a sequence of these "models" – one per decade – is then presented as the great success to be emulated.
The most successful societies of the future will allow room for experiments and will permit further evolution of their institutions.
A world economy that recognizes the need and value of institutional diversity will foster such an experimental attitude and evolutionary development rather than repress it.
4. Countries have the right to protect their own rules and institutions.
The above principles may seem harmless.
But they carry powerful implications that conflict with the prevailing view of globalization supporters.
One such implication is the right of individual countries to protect their national institutional decisions.
The recognition of institutional diversity would be meaningless if countries did not have the tools at their disposal to shape and preserve their own institutions – in a word: to „protect“ them.
We should therefore accept that countries can maintain national rules – tax policy, financial regulation, labor standards or rules protecting consumer health and safety – and that they are allowed to do so by possibly erecting barriers at their borders if trade demonstrably threatens homegrown practices that enjoy broad support among the population.
Do proponents of globalization have it right, protection measures of this sort will fail due to a lack of evidence or support.
Do they have it wrong, there is a safety valve that allows conflicting values – the benefits of open economies and the benefits of maintaining national regulations – to be heard appropriately in public debates.
5. Countries have no right to impose their own institutions on others.
The use of restrictions in cross-border trade or in the financial sector to maintain values and rules in one's own country is not to be confused with their use to force other countries to adopt these values and rules.
The rules of globalization should not force Americans or Europeans to consume goods produced in a way that most citizens in these countries find unacceptable.
No more, however, should they enable the US or the EU to impose trade sanctions or other pressure on other countries to change their labor market regulations, environmental policies, or financial regulations.
Countries have a right to diversity, not to forced convergence.

6. International economic agreements for regulating interactions between national institutions: Relying on national states to provide the basic steering functions of the world economy does not mean that we should abandon international rules.
The Bretton Woods system, after all, also had clear rules, even if they were limited in scope and depth.
A complete laissez-faire would not benefit anyone.
What we need are traffic rules for the world economy that help vehicles of different size, shape, and speed to pass each other, rather than prescribing an identical car or a uniform speed limit.
We should strive to achieve a maximum level of globalization that is in line with preserving the space for diversity in national institutional arrangements.
7. Non-democratic countries cannot count on the same rights and privileges in the international economic order as democracies.
What gives the aforementioned principles their attractiveness and legitimacy is that they are based on democratic deliberation – where this really happens, within the nation-states.
If states are not democratic, this framework collapses.
We can no longer assume that their institutional arrangements reflect the preferences of their citizens.
For non-democratic countries, therefore, other, less liberal rules must apply.
These are the principles that the architects of the next world economic order must accept.
Most important is that they must ultimately accept the paradox that each of these principles illustrates: Globalization works best when you don't take it too far.
